{"cursor":"16455","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n{{Infobox_Company | company_name = Meyer Sound Laboratories | company_logo = |\ncompany_type = Professional Audio Manufacturer | foundation = 1979 |\nlocation_city = Berkeley, CA | location_country = United States | key_people =\nJohn & Helen Meyer, Founders | industry = Professional Audio | products =\nLoudspeakers, Digital Audio Systems, Audio Analysis Tools | revenue = |\nnum_employees = |200+ homepage = [http://www.meyersound.com/\nwww.meyersound.com] }}\n\n'Meyer Sound Laboratories' is an American company based in Berkeley, California\nthat manufactures self-powered loudspeakers, multichannel audio show control\nsystems, electroacoustic architecture, and audio analysis tools for the\nprofessional sound reinforcement, fixed installation, and sound recording\nindustries.\n\nThe companyâs emphasis on research and measurement has resulted in the issuance\nof dozens of patents, including for the now-standard trapezoidal loudspeaker\ncabinet shape. http://www.meyersound.com/about/patents/ [http://p-\natft.uspto.gov/netacgi/nph-\nParser?Sect1=PTO2&Sect2=HITOFF&p=1&u=%2Fnetahtml%2FPTO%2Fsearch-\nbool.html&r=0&f=S&l=50&TERM1=meyer+sound&FIELD1=ASNM&co1=AND&TERM2=&FIELD2=&d=P-\nTXT United States Patent and Trademark Office - Meyer Sound patents] Meyer\nSound has pioneered other technologies that have become standard in the audio\nindustry, including: processor-controlled loudspeaker systems, self-powered lou-\ndspeakers, [http://mixonline.com/live/applications/audio_necessity_mothers_-\ninvention/ \"Necessity Mothers Invention\"] Maureen Droney, Mix magazine, Nov 2004 [http://www.meyersound.com/about/our_story/pioneering_self-\npowered/ Pioneering Self-Powered Loudspeakers for Over 11 Years]\ncurvilinear arraying, cardioid subwoofers, and source independent measurement.\n\nMeyer Sound has consistently involved itself with advanced research beyond that\nconnected to immediate product development, sometimes in conjunction with arms\nof the University of California, Berkeley. Some of this research has resulted in\nunusual products such as their parabolic sound beam and sound field synthesis\nloudspeakers. Other projects, such as the spherical loudspeaker research\nunderway by Meyer Sound and CNMAT (Center for New Music and Audio Technologies)\nat UC\nBerkeley [http://cnmat.berkeley.edu/research/spherical_loudspeaker_array UC\nBerkeley, Research. Spherical Loudspeaker Array] are still in the stage of\npure research.\n","linknr":187,"url":"Meyer_Sound_Laboratories","recorded":1363148075,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Meyer_Sound_Laboratories&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Meyer_Sound_Laboratories&action=edit","//en.wikipedia.org/apple-touch-icon.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.wikihiero%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-head","#p-search","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/f/f4/Ambox_content.png","/wiki/Wikipedia:NOT#SOAPBOX","//en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=Meyer_Sound_Laboratories&action=edit","/wiki/Wikipedia:Neutral_point_of_view","/wiki/Wikipedia:EL","/wiki/File:Meyersoundlogo.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/a/ae/Meyersoundlogo.jpg/70px-Meyersoundlogo.jpg","/wiki/Types_of_business_entity","/wiki/Sound_reproduction","/wiki/Loudspeaker","/wiki/Berkeley,_California","/